                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/45980",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=kblomqvist",
                        "name": "kblomqvist",
                        "displayName": "Kim Blomqvist",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "I don't see the problem here. You have specified the count and offset in {{limit(1,10)}}, so why not use {{$table->fetchAll($select)}} then? In my opinion, the key use case here is do we have to assemble the select object or could we quick fetch a row like this ...\r\n\r\n{code}\r\n$row = $table->fetchRow(array('colour = ?' => 'orange'), null, 10);\r\n{code}\r\n\r\nOf course to get this work, we have to add an $offset parameter into the {{fetchRow}} method ...\r\n\r\n{code}\r\npublic function fetchRow($where = null, $order = null, $offset = null)\r\n{code}",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=kblomqvist",
                        "name": "kblomqvist",
                        "displayName": "Kim Blomqvist",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2011-04-22T22:40:09.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2011-04-22T22:40:09.000+0000"
                },
